column9: I write here out of concern that customers because of a preference for the touchscreen capability will be tempted to purchase the more updated "touchscreen" version of NURSAL combination TENS/EMS:  https://www.amazon.com/NURSAL-Combination-Management-Rehabilitation-Electronic/dp/B752DNKJ9/ref=sr_1_5_a_it?ie=UTF8&qid=1527796598&sr=8-5&keywords=NURSAL over this unit . That touchscreen version whose link I just provided is absolutely. NOT a combination unit; it is merely a TENS unit. Upon receipt I could not ascertain how to use the EMS aspect and no reference of it was anywhere in the provided manual. I checked with my physical therapist and he advised me that it does not have the EMS capability. I noticed the lovely box in which it arrived labeled it as a "(TENS)" unit. Affixed to that box was a small SKU-type sticker with small print reading, "Combination unit".  However, putting on a new little label stating that a device is XYZ does not miraculously transform the device into XYZ! It is false advertising. Few would be the people who make the purchase without a need for it. This patient was in severe pain with atrophy from disuse when ordering that device and the delay caused by the return process only extended the days without relief.You might wonder why I am taking so much time to write this commentary here. Yes, I want to warn others of the issue but, beyond that, the product for the touchscreen device is "not accepting reviews" at this time.Good Luck to you all as you seek relief from pain.Hopefully the standard combination unit described here lives up to its advertising and is, indeed, a combination unit. The NURSAL touchscreen version

column9: I LLIKE IT

Bought this for chronic back and neck pain. Obviously I wasn't expecting the same quality as the chiro's equipment but definitely not nearly the same. The patches don't adhere strongly enough in my opinion. You tend to feel a shock occasionally. I though maybe I had some bad patches or a bad unit but a friend has the same one and he said he gets the exact same thing. So I decided to try some electrode gel, thinking it will reduce my shock...it did not. I have purchased more pads so I hope maybe those will work better than the ones that came with the unit.The unit is extremely light. The battery life is excellent (don't bother with any unit that does NOT have a lithium battery). I wish the backlight stayed on a bit longer. Goes out within a few seconds (and I mean a few). Touchscreen is a bit cheesy. Quality isn't there. Don't expect it to be like a smartphone display. As far as instructions...forget it. For a unit like this I was expecting a lot more with clearer instructions. You're basically on your own. I found several diagrams online as far as placement but the instructions are not clear on using A and B channels and white/aqua wire ends are (positive or negative or neither?).When the unit isn't shocking me it works nice. You typically can't go more than half power on most settings (not sure what they all are because the instructions don't tell you...you just have to try them all).

column9: I've held off on reviewing this until I'd really had a chance to put some time in on it. There are so many raving reviews that I had to keep my expectations in check a bit. Here's my experience:BACKGROUND: I am plagued by regular lower back, leg, and neck pain as a result of having been hit by a car in a crosswalk 6 years ago. My physical therapist, chiropractor, and pain management docs have all either used, or recommended, TENS as something that might help. It has. I finally decided to buy a unit I could use at home for both convenience and, honestly, I was also trying to save a few bucks (doc visits are pricy!).PROS: Convenience, definitely. It's nice to be able to grab this of the nightstand and get a session on whenever I need one. I've taken it camping and being able to recharge it (through i haven't had to yet) with my battery bank is a huge plus. The battery life on this thing is really good! I can't tell you how many times I've used it (lots!) and the battery indicator hasn't dropped even a bar yet! The unit works really well as long as I'm only using a single (2 pad) lead.CONS: The unit ONLY seems to work well when I'm using a single (2 pad) lead. When I try adding a second lead, or even using the 4 pad lead it fails. I feel dramatically diminished activity in one set of pads and almost nothing in the other. I have to really crank it up for it to perform as well as with a single lead and I still feel next to nothing in the second set of pads.OVERALL: I'm not entirely certain I'm disappointed enough to return it (though I may). It would easily have been a 5 star purchase for me if it worked with 4 or 6 pads as stated in the description and numerous reviews.

column9: PRO:- charging convenience, no charger needed, regular micro USB will work fine.- small- Li-Ion battery meaning you can charge at any time without damaging the batteries. no memory effect- 4 nozzles included, 2 more can be ordered free of charge from their websiteCONTRA:- poor design of the buttons position. They are very low positioned and makes difficult to switch modes during flossing. There is a very similar design on Amazon (Guisee water flosser) with buttons positioned easy to reach with your thumb- charging time: way above 10h. Tried with 2 different chargers (Anker and Samsung). The current taken from the charger is about 200mA (5V) meaning that wirelessly will get even lower (cannot measure unless I disassemble the unit which I didn't). No mention anywhere about the Li-Ion battery capacity, I assume it is around 1500 mA based on similar model (Guisee). On a full charge, 30 sec time floss will require about 1.5 min to full charge again only if you are using their wireless charger. Any other standard or fast charge wireless charger will keep charging so don't do this as the batteries might get damaged.- VERY noisy. I estimate is twice as noisy compared with Panasonic EW1211W which I have- the nozzle hole is a bit bigger than Panasonic meaning more water but less precision. In the end the time to floss is shorter even if the water tank is 30% bigger. I basically need to fill the tank twice to get the same result I get from Panasonic- the product is advertised as travel friendly but no pouch or travel case included- on their official website the product is pictured but no other details or user manual download option. This make me wonder about product's service support.

The one set of pads I tried was fine. Plenty of power in this little unit. But useless because you have no control over the settings. As a Certified Athletic Trainer (ATC), I actually know how these are supposed to operate and what settings to use for what purpose (pain control, muscle spasm, strengthening, etc.). This unit will do none of that. I should be able to control frequency, ramp on/off, etc. not just pick a "mode". I can go to the nail salon massage chairs for that.This is not a true TENS unit--hardly any better than one of those silly things you put in your chair for a "massage". Cute little gadget, but it's of no medical use, whatsoever. While there are 16 "modes", none of the settings are adjustable and none of the 16 modes is a continuous one. All are intermittent. So if you like an obnoxious on/off setting that you have no control over, then you'll be set with this unit. Otherwise, look for something else.

column9: I'm torn on how to review this because it works really well, is more powerful than I thought it would be, and after only a day of use my back is in a much better place. The reason for three stars is that it's advertised as a TENS EMS Combo yet there is no mention of EMS anywhere on the package or in the manual. I chose this one because it's rechargeable and has the combo, EMS comes at a premium to the standard TENS units so it's kind of important to know. Based on my understanding of the two I feel like I'm getting the combined benefits, but without separate TENS/EMS modes or knowing what/if they feel different I have know way of knowing if i got what I though I was getting. Thought to contact the manufacturer, but the contact information is just an address in China.Edit: On day two the second electrode port stopped working so now I can only treat one area at a time. The evidence is coming together that this is overpriced, cheap Chinese junk.Second Edit: Now day three neither outputs work. i'm stuck with an $80 piece of useless plastic. I sure hope amazon's excellent customer service makes this better.

I'm a little disappointed with this product. It is too heavy in my hand and even on the lowest setting, at times the vibration is too much on my shoulders. Also the heat feature takes a while to heat up and only feels warm at best.

A bit cumbersome and hard to keep in right place behind neck when laying back against a pillow to watch a movie or read in bed. Heat didn't work at all so I returned it. Also, cord is kind of short for controls so annoying when you try to change setting if you are already in position.

I returned this product.  Not sure what I did wrong, I just can't get it to work right on the arm to take correct measurement, the instruction is not clear to me either.  I don't think there is anything wrong wit the machine, just can't get it to work correctly.

This product is constructed very well. The accessories are also of great quality. Here is the only thing I didn't like about this product. The water pressure or strength of the spray is quite weak. Their popular competitor has 3 speeds where 1 is equal to TEC Bean's normal and highest strengths speed.  I'm sorry but had to return due to its ineffectiveness as a water pik/floss.

I got this for my six year-old so he could have something to listen to when he goes to sleep, but there were several issues: 1) It can only be setup in military time--not great for a young child in the US 2) the display does not stay backlit more than a minute so you can't see the time without full room lights on or without pressing the power button which activates the sound--makes it essentially useless as a bedroom clock 3) while it has volume control, the lowest level is not actually very low.I suppose if you want a noise machine that won't necessarily be on your night table directly next to you, this could work. The timer is a nice feature. But as a combo clock/sound machine, it just doesn't work.
